'''Pekka Tirkkonen''' (born July 17, 1968) is a [[Finland|Finnish]] ice hockey coach and former professional [[ice hockey]] player. He most recently served as head coach of [[EHC Kloten]] of the [[National League (ice hockey)|National League]] (NL). Tirkkonen was selected by the [[Boston Bruins]] in the 2nd round (34th overall) of the [[1986 NHL Entry Draft]].<ref>http://bruins.nhl.com/club/player.htm?id=8458225</ref>

== Playing career ==
Tirkkonen played 14 seasons in Finnland's top-tier [[SM-liiga]], registering 161 goals, 236 assists, 397 points, and 241 penalty minutes, in 647 games played for [[HC TPS]], [[KalPa]] and [[SaiPa]]. He won the championship with TPS in 1989, 1990 and 1991.

Other stops in his playing career included Germany ([[Starbulls Rosenheim]], [[Augsburger Panther]]), Sweden ([[Linköpings HC|Linköping HC]]) and Denmark ([[Herning Blue Fox]]). He claimed the Danish championship with Herning in 2005, 2007 and 2008, before retiring following the 2007-08 season.

== Coaching career ==
Tirkkonen kicked off his career behind the bench immediately after retiring as a player and was appointed as head coach of Finnish second division side [[SaPKo]] prior to the 2008-09 season. After four year at the helm and after receiving [[Mestis]] Coach of the Year honors in 2012, he moved on and was named head coach of [[SaiPa]] of the country's top-tier [[Liiga]] ahead of the 2012-13 campaign. In the 2013-14 season, Tirkkonen won the [[Kalevi Numminen trophy|Kalevi Numminen Trophy]] as the league's Coach of the Year. He guided SaiPa to the Liiga semifinals that season, where they fell short to eventual champions [[Oulun Kärpät|Kärpät]].

Tirkkonen parted ways with [[SaiPa]] following the 2015-16 season and was named head coach of [[Kloten Flyers|EHC Kloten]] of the [[National League (ice hockey)|National League]] (NL) on June 24, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ehc-kloten.ch/news/nl-a/news-berichte/medienmitteilung_240616/|title=Medienmitteilung_240616 - EHC Kloten|website=EHC Kloten|language=de-DE|access-date=2016-06-24}}</ref> He was fired on October 16, 2017, following poor coaching performances.

